diff:1670528442:1670119476:=55,72c55%0a%3c #foxbegin 221208-194043-914540#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!more on sign language  %0a%3c -> - tingchen%0a%3c -> [-08.12.2022 - 11:40-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221208-194043-914540 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Sign language, although sometimes not taken as a language (as it is not verbal), is in fact a language! It requires the very same part of brain to process information as other languages and it has ambiguities, which makes double-meaning jokes. Also, sign language has slangs and modified slangs. Like in British Sign Language, the idiom "in one ear, out the other" is changed into "in one eye, out the other". “Divorce” is articulated as “throw your ring to the ground”. These idioms suggest, sign languages also have dialects and accents.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.distractify.com/humor/2018/12/10/hgdvoEy/sign-language-jokes%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221208-194043-914540#%0a---%0a> %0a
